author: @georgeide2337
comments:
It depends on the cost basis he had when he purchased the stock. When Buffett purchased so much Apple stock, he did so at a bargain. Of course, that meant his total interest/profit was much higher and would therefore still "lose" money, but it was unrealized wealth and so of less consequence than if he had a larger cost basis.
If you buy 100 stocks at $1 and over 20 years those shares are worth $100 a share but crash before you can sell, you only lose $100. Someone who bought in at $50+ on the other hand would have lost $5000 plus their unrealized returns.


This is why single stocks are no longer a good bet for the average investor. There aren't many of these undervalued companies in this information age, so cost basis is more often than not very high. Back in the days of Buffett, he wasn't competing with the internet/institutions we are today, and he will be the first to admit that.

Imagine having $5M worth of Apple stock and seeing it evaporate overnight. If you diversify it, that would simply not happen.

I'd keep 20% of those stocks in Apple and diversify the rest.

author: @KungPowEnterFist
comments: 99% of what you are saying is the past.  Because Apple did well in the past, they will do well in the future.  This causes more people to lose money in the stock market than anything else.  At best, Apple is a big money safe haven as we head into recession.  Meaning, you will lose less money on Apple than other stocks or sectors.  Its the same reason why big money is pouring into utilities and consumer defensive.  Those sectors are going down from here, but they won't go down as much as other sectors.  Unlike the retail investor, they can't just get out of the market and go all cash.  They have to keep the vast majority in play at all times, and so you want the money in what will lose the least.  As I have said many times, if you saw the signs and heeded them you would have gone all cash at the end of 2021 with maybe the exception of energy.  This is not hindsight.  It was obvious.  The overall stock market including Apple is headed down from here.  $250 a share by end of 2022 is not going to happen.  You will be lucky if its $150 a share, and since Apple pays a crap dividend there really is no reason to hold other than for emotional reasons.  Which is fine.

author: @firasabbasi9715
comments:
Thank you. Very informative. Share buy backs are funded with either cash or debt. Let‚Äôs assume it‚Äôs cash which is what current shareholders already own.
Manufacturing earnings is a way of trading current value for future value. It‚Äôs a signal of confidence by the company. It‚Äôs not magic.
P/E valuation (pricing more accurately) doesn‚Äôt - at least not  directly - take into account the amount of cash the company holds or the debt the company owes.
A company can buy back shares and lower p/e funded by borrowed funds which can be a good strategy but needs further analysis. Obviously Appl has great future earnings potential that a share buy back is welcome!
Great video! As always. Thanks for the high quality content.

author: @GB-ws8zx
comments: A very interesting vid.  Among the factors challenging my analysis, I'm not aware of any precedent for Apple's situation at greater than 2T (it's not about size alone, this type of company (with unique culture, brand and products/services) existing in this field), and the same questions you seem to ask: Could they grow more/how could they grow more? seem to be challenging certain assumptions/beliefs I hold.  I'm certain they are overvalued in the short term due to COVID/TINA, but, having studied Apple's unique philosophy for years, while numbers concern me, I have full confidence in the core culture that Jobs created, to both create and adapt.  Many can talk about trying to mimic Apple's approach, but I see few seeming to truly do it, or do it well.  For this reason, while I do think the current price is likely divorced from fundamentals, Apple's approach to creating a well-designed future (think both car and AR) really challenge my assumptions about what options exist once a company gets into the 2 - 3T range or beyond.  It's sheer size + geopolitical risks + transitioning to profits via services just raise A LOT of questions whose answers don't seem immediately clear.  Also, my guess: doubt along with the question of how could they grow more? weighs on the minds of many, and will require real evidence to resolve.

author: @Lord_Falcon
comments:
I've never understood why most people buy Apple products. I suppose there's the brand factor because people think it's American & luxury/high quality but anyone that has common sense shouldn't buy them. Why? 
1) They're extremely expensive. Considering most people in the US have less than $1000 in savings it's insane for people to buy them or get them on expensive contacts.
2) Quality is poor for the price which is intentional to force people into expensive repairs or just buying a new device.
3) Apple constantly pisses people off by changing ports to force buying new accessories with every device.
4) They routinely makes older devices worse via software updates to force you into replacing.
5) They often reduce functionality of apps that provide competing services to their own in an attempt to force you to use theirs even if it sucks (which it often does). E.g. Apple Music vs Spotify.
As an investment prospect I don't like Apple partly because of the reasons above but mainly because they have failed to build the brand hype outside the US. There's a few European countries with strong sales but it's not at all like the US.  They have about 50% US market share but to maintain this they've had to release cheaper models in recent years. This hurts their "luxury" brand image. They're stuck between a rock & a hard place. Either de-value the brand with affordable products and become just another ordinary smartphone maker or stay really expensive and eventualy become a niche high priced brand. But then the products have to get better which will reduce margins.

author: @Defomir
comments: Oh god, IMHO you are not getting the point about innovation and Apple. Their products didn't change in last 3 years. iPhone 13 and iPhone 14 are the same phones (with 2gb rams added to newer one). And across the World prices are higher than Android counterparts (fun fact, you have to pay 849 GBP for basic version of iPhone 14, when in US it cost 799 USD, check GBPUSD value - atm for one GBP  you get 1.17 USD). They skyrocket prices outside US, with no new value added to product, and they event 'adjusted' prices up of old devices (like iPhone 13 or Macbook Air M1), because of inflation (and the prices of new devices wont be looking so scary). Well because of that inflation less people will be changing their devices to new ones - they have to pay more for same stuff, so why change? I'm currently sitting on iPhone X, and wanted to change for 13 or 14 depending on whats new in 14. Guess I won't be changing at all with this price policy, I can wait another year for iPhone 15. Share buybacks are awesome, I agree, but they are awesome when you buy your shares CHEAP, not on 25-35 PE. That's actually waste of shareholders money. Yeah, I know they have like 200 billions so they have to do something with the money. Maybe innovative products? ;-) I agree on software and services stuff. Issue is - if you don't sale phones and users are leaving, then to who you will sell services? Check the iPhone sells - from 2015 it stagnated. And that's the issue with Apple that investors have right now. Money part is a check - for now, but it can be whole different story in a year from now.

author: @davidpaterson7142
comments:
Nice analysis - however one point I disagree on is your opinion that Apple should increase their dividend or issue a special dividend. It is worth noting that dividends are taxed heavily and so it makes much more sense for the company to use any additional funds for further buybacks. If an investor needs income then they can simply sell some of their shares, and any capital gain will be far more tax advantageous than receiving a dividend. Not to mention the benefit of allowing the investor to choose when they do and don't get taxed on this gain. As you even mention yourself, that most investors would probably take the dividend and simply reinvest in the company, this would be a completely unnecessary loss of capital due to the tax deduction, plus any additional dealing costs.

In addition to the above, buybacks also help to reduce volatility in the stock which is an added benefit for investors. When the markets are taking a dive there is great comfort in knowing the company is continuing the buyback its own shares providing support to the price.

author: @santoshragi
comments:
FYI, Alphabet pays ~$15 billion to Apple for preloading Google search app. All of that ~$15 billion pretty much goes to Apple's bottom line. That payment could stop over time if:
1) new regulations (especially given the shifting sentiment across the world on antitrust regulation) prohibit such preload payments; or 
2) if Alphabet realizes that there is no need for making such a payment as Google search app is likely to be downloaded by the end user.
That's big chunk of cashflow for Apple & they might have to recoup that in other ways. It is for sure a risk to consider.

author: @xmoney1
comments:
Guys can i ask you a "stupid" question? I really changed my whole approach on investing after i found your channel. 
I just can't understand the assumption that a company with a very low P/E ratio like 6 or 7, will eventually have a higher one.
Is it not possible for a company to continue growing its revenues but the P/E stays at those low levels??
Im asking because if we change the assumptions of the P/E from 12 to 20 (which you use most of the time) to 7-8-9 for example, the prices we get at the analyze tool are way lower.
And i checked a lot of companies with very good growth, no liabilites, no share dilution etc etc but their P/E was very low.
How can we be sure that in the future it will be higher and this will drive the stock price at higher levels?
Because at the end of the day, the price of any stock goes up or down based on the demand.
I know its a stupid question, but its changing almost everything on my analysis while im trying to have a more realistic assumptions.
Thanks in advance.

author: @DhavalBrahmbhatt2627
comments:
Constructive feedback: Your PE multiple being lower than 22 method is not correct. In your videos about the smallest companies to the biggest one, you apply the same PE expectations. In your own words, you say that the validation defers from company to company depending on what they do. In your own words, you say that large companies can‚Äôt grow as quickly as smaller companies. Still you apply the same PE to both. So the PE needs to be dependent on how large the company is or the % of TAM they have covered. Work out a formula and that will make more sense than a fixed figure to apply across the board.

Mo saying Amazon sells EVERYthing and they will do 111bn vs Apple only seelling iDevices and they will still do 89bn. Complete wrong comparison. Amazon is broker, they only take commission on any item they sell depends on the price of the item and is not in their own hands. Apple makes stuff themselves and hence it is completely down to them how much margin they wanna make. Add to the fact that Apple‚Äôs stuff is way overpriced (surely you guys know about things being overpriced). So on fair value basis, their revenue would be more like 50 to 60bn. The reason they make 89bn is because they are greedy as hell and they have the right to sell it whatever price they want because ppl buy it for the  brand name. 

So if we consider all that together, it isn‚Äôt really that incredible. What is incredible is that it is actually happening whether I like it or not but if you really apply your logic of fair value, it isn‚Äôt. 

Love their produces when assessed objectively on their merits (except price) but hate the company.

author: @Dcmorris1991
comments: IMO this is not great day trading advice. Adding to your position on engulfing candle sticks for day trades is more akin to chasing a move rather than adding on conviction. That's a real dangerous play because you leave yourself no room for a stop loss on a sudden move to the upside. You want to add to a position when the short term trend is moving in the opposite direction of what you want, but the overall larger trend is still in your favor. This example here was lucky with engulfing all the way down, but this type of move is definitely an exception, not the rule.

Both the UK and US publish numbers of the subject and see similar ratios. 

In summary, women are seen as being less capable of being devious so when a men is involved they are seen as followers (this was a key argument from Holmes' defence) and they are also more likely to have mitigating circumstances because they look after the elderly and kids at a higher proportion. Not saying either of those reasons are "fair" on women, but we shouldn't ignore what is a clear difference in sentencing purely based on gender. 

Arguably, the most important area of all where equality matters is before the law, and I don't see that at all. Whether you're a Classical Liberal (so right leaning) caring about equality of opportunity, of or a Progressive Liberal (so left leaning) caring about equality of outcome, the whole situation should leave a very poor taste in the mouth. 

Holmes should absolutely have been found similarly guilty. That would be equality worth fighting for.

author: @traumflug
comments: Nice video. These considerations on how to deal with AAPL options is kind of a reversed sunk cost fallacy, though. Just like one shouldn't look at money already lost when planning on how to proceed, one also shouldn't look at money already earned. If these options are 106% up now and you decide something which reduces this to 80% up, you didn't gain 80%, but lost 25%, it was a bad decision. When doing decisions, one should always look at the situation right at that moment, and on how it might develop from there. Earlier gains don't matter.

author: @DhavalBrahmbhatt2627
comments:
Constructive feedback: Your PE multiple being lower than 22 method is not correct. In your videos about the smallest companies to the biggest one, you apply the same PE expectations. In your own words, you say that the validation defers from company to company depending on what they do. In your own words, you say that large companies can‚Äôt grow as quickly as smaller companies. Still you apply the same PE to both. So the PE needs to be dependent on how large the company is or the % of TAM they have covered. Work out a formula and that will make more sense than a fixed figure to apply across the board.

Mo saying Amazon sells EVERYthing and they will do 111bn vs Apple only seelling iDevices and they will still do 89bn. Complete wrong comparison. Amazon is broker, they only take commission on any item they sell depends on the price of the item and is not in their own hands. Apple makes stuff themselves and hence it is completely down to them how much margin they wanna make. Add to the fact that Apple‚Äôs stuff is way overpriced (surely you guys know about things being overpriced). So on fair value basis, their revenue would be more like 50 to 60bn. The reason they make 89bn is because they are greedy as hell and they have the right to sell it whatever price they want because ppl buy it for the  brand name. 

So if we consider all that together, it isn‚Äôt really that incredible. What is incredible is that it is actually happening whether I like it or not but if you really apply your logic of fair value, it isn‚Äôt. 

Love their produces when assessed objectively on their merits (except price) but hate the company.

author: @GB-ws8zx
comments: A very interesting vid.  Among the factors challenging my analysis, I'm not aware of any precedent for Apple's situation at greater than 2T (it's not about size alone, this type of company (with unique culture, brand and products/services) existing in this field), and the same questions you seem to ask: Could they grow more/how could they grow more? seem to be challenging certain assumptions/beliefs I hold.  I'm certain they are overvalued in the short term due to COVID/TINA, but, having studied Apple's unique philosophy for years, while numbers concern me, I have full confidence in the core culture that Jobs created, to both create and adapt.  Many can talk about trying to mimic Apple's approach, but I see few seeming to truly do it, or do it well.  For this reason, while I do think the current price is likely divorced from fundamentals, Apple's approach to creating a well-designed future (think both car and AR) really challenge my assumptions about what options exist once a company gets into the 2 - 3T range or beyond.  It's sheer size + geopolitical risks + transitioning to profits via services just raise A LOT of questions whose answers don't seem immediately clear.  Also, my guess: doubt along with the question of how could they grow more? weighs on the minds of many, and will require real evidence to resolve.

author: @rogergeyer9851
comments:
I buy a fair amount of LEAPS in growth stocks I like a lot.  In this case, I'd prefer to use the 2024 Jan. 150 call, and pay about 26, vs. the 2023 Jan 150 call and pay about 18.5.  So nearly double the time for only about 40 percent more premium. 

The Jan 2024  LEAPS 150 call trades about half the volume of the 2023, so it's reasonable volume.  Also, if concerned about thin trading, just use a limit order to ensure you get a reasonable price.  If you place such an order at the midpoint between the bid and asked, you'll generally get filled.

author: @Lord_Falcon
comments:
I've never understood why most people buy Apple products. I suppose there's the brand factor because people think it's American & luxury/high quality but anyone that has common sense shouldn't buy them. Why? 
1) They're extremely expensive. Considering most people in the US have less than $1000 in savings it's insane for people to buy them or get them on expensive contacts.
2) Quality is poor for the price which is intentional to force people into expensive repairs or just buying a new device.
3) Apple constantly pisses people off by changing ports to force buying new accessories with every device.
4) They routinely makes older devices worse via software updates to force you into replacing.
5) They often reduce functionality of apps that provide competing services to their own in an attempt to force you to use theirs even if it sucks (which it often does). E.g. Apple Music vs Spotify.
As an investment prospect I don't like Apple partly because of the reasons above but mainly because they have failed to build the brand hype outside the US. There's a few European countries with strong sales but it's not at all like the US.  They have about 50% US market share but to maintain this they've had to release cheaper models in recent years. This hurts their "luxury" brand image. They're stuck between a rock & a hard place. Either de-value the brand with affordable products and become just another ordinary smartphone maker or stay really expensive and eventualy become a niche high priced brand. But then the products have to get better which will reduce margins.

author: @eddierazak
comments:
Hi Ziet, great channel!
Maybe you can do a video about capital gains tax.

Many people don't know that we (non-US residents) have an advantage over people in the US when it comes to investing. US citizens and residents are subject to capital gains tax on US stocks. For non-US residents there is no capital gains tax.

So for Malaysians and Singaporeans for example, if your Tesla stock goes up, you make all of the upside when you sell, whereas US residents lose some of that gain to tax.

However, there is still tax on dividends of US stocks, which applies to everyone. So, it may be better to maximise the gains from stocks that don't pay dividends, like Tesla, instead of stocks like Apple, where you lose some dividends to tax.

author: @davidpaterson7142
comments:
Nice analysis - however one point I disagree on is your opinion that Apple should increase their dividend or issue a special dividend. It is worth noting that dividends are taxed heavily and so it makes much more sense for the company to use any additional funds for further buybacks. If an investor needs income then they can simply sell some of their shares, and any capital gain will be far more tax advantageous than receiving a dividend. Not to mention the benefit of allowing the investor to choose when they do and don't get taxed on this gain. As you even mention yourself, that most investors would probably take the dividend and simply reinvest in the company, this would be a completely unnecessary loss of capital due to the tax deduction, plus any additional dealing costs.

In addition to the above, buybacks also help to reduce volatility in the stock which is an added benefit for investors. When the markets are taking a dive there is great comfort in knowing the company is continuing the buyback its own shares providing support to the price.

author: @Dcmorris1991
comments: IMO this is not great day trading advice. Adding to your position on engulfing candle sticks for day trades is more akin to chasing a move rather than adding on conviction. That's a real dangerous play because you leave yourself no room for a stop loss on a sudden move to the upside. You want to add to a position when the short term trend is moving in the opposite direction of what you want, but the overall larger trend is still in your favor. This example here was lucky with engulfing all the way down, but this type of move is definitely an exception, not the rule.

author: @georgeide2337
comments:
It depends on the cost basis he had when he purchased the stock. When Buffett purchased so much Apple stock, he did so at a bargain. Of course, that meant his total interest/profit was much higher and would therefore still "lose" money, but it was unrealized wealth and so of less consequence than if he had a larger cost basis.
If you buy 100 stocks at $1 and over 20 years those shares are worth $100 a share but crash before you can sell, you only lose $100. Someone who bought in at $50+ on the other hand would have lost $5000 plus their unrealized returns.


This is why single stocks are no longer a good bet for the average investor. There aren't many of these undervalued companies in this information age, so cost basis is more often than not very high. Back in the days of Buffett, he wasn't competing with the internet/institutions we are today, and he will be the first to admit that.

author: @mahadevovnl
comments:
Apple can easily go the way of Yahoo, Altavista, AOL, Netscape, MySpace, Napster, Digg... the list goes on and on. Very popular at their heights, dead in no-time. It wouldn't take much, either. Imagine having $5M worth of Apple stock and seeing it evaporate overnight. If you diversify it, that would simply not happen.

Yet, if you diversify it and their stock never tanks, you might miss out on many millions down the road. High risk versus high reward.

I'd keep 20% of those stocks in Apple and diversify the rest.

comments: An economy cannot keep buying and spending, it is unsustainable.  The period of unbridled buying and spending began before 2008-2009, after that, with QE, this behaviour became entrenched. We consume less and focus more on recycling or prolonging the lifespan of our consumables.  I am happily using a iPhone6, and finding ways to repurpose my iphone5.  I hope the economy will now move back to less consumerism and more savings for the long run.  Maybe it is bad for many of the stocks, with much less earnings, but it would be good for the world over the long term.

Literally AAPL can split its business and the stock will jump cuz each business is an equivalent of a large cap business based on their revenue of that segment.  
With buy backs and dividend it is a safe buy and hold stock.  Maybe not a multi bagger in one year but certainly one every 5 years.

author: @GB-ws8zx
comments: A very interesting vid.  Among the factors challenging my analysis, I'm not aware of any precedent for Apple's situation at greater than 2T (it's not about size alone, this type of company (with unique culture, brand and products/services) existing in this field), and the same questions you seem to ask: Could they grow more/how could they grow more? seem to be challenging certain assumptions/beliefs I hold.  I'm certain they are overvalued in the short term due to COVID/TINA, but, having studied Apple's unique philosophy for years, while numbers concern me, I have full confidence in the core culture that Jobs created, to both create and adapt.  Many can talk about trying to mimic Apple's approach, but I see few seeming to truly do it, or do it well.  For this reason, while I do think the current price is likely divorced from fundamentals, Apple's approach to creating a well-designed future (think both car and AR) really challenge my assumptions about what options exist once a company gets into the 2 - 3T range or beyond.  It's sheer size + geopolitical risks + transitioning to profits via services just raise A LOT of questions whose answers don't seem immediately clear.  Also, my guess: doubt along with the question of how could they grow more? weighs on the minds of many, and will require real evidence to resolve.

2022 Rumor: AR Glasses (The Holy Grail of Wearables)
Other Potential Tailwinds for 2022:

Introduction of foldable iPhones (big maybe)
Services will continue to expand and services command a higher earnings multiple
Gradual removal of Qualcomm chips will expand margins
Stupid amounts of share buybacks
Supply Chain Headwind goes away
Inflation Headwind should softens
Rotation from Ultra High Growth stocks into Megacaps in 2022
Global Growth normalizing in 2022 will make comps for Value stocks hard to beat and that'll cause a rotation from Value to Megacaps

The company will never get the funds or support in the stock market.

Worth thinking about.

Yes, we‚Äôre seeing the same exact thing in my industry - a massive, sweeping drop in orders because inventories are already way too high because no one is buying anything right now when their utilities bill is $500/month instead of what it used to be ($175-225), and when energy prices in general are still way too high and inflation is slapping us in the face every month with a 2-4% added premium.

Buckle up.

comments:
Constructive feedback: Your PE multiple being lower than 22 method is not correct. In your videos about the smallest companies to the biggest one, you apply the same PE expectations. In your own words, you say that the validation defers from company to company depending on what they do. In your own words, you say that large companies can‚Äôt grow as quickly as smaller companies. Still you apply the same PE to both. So the PE needs to be dependent on how large the company is or the % of TAM they have covered. Work out a formula and that will make more sense than a fixed figure to apply across the board.

Mo saying Amazon sells EVERYthing and they will do 111bn vs Apple only seelling iDevices and they will still do 89bn. Complete wrong comparison. Amazon is broker, they only take commission on any item they sell depends on the price of the item and is not in their own hands. Apple makes stuff themselves and hence it is completely down to them how much margin they wanna make. Add to the fact that Apple‚Äôs stuff is way overpriced (surely you guys know about things being overpriced). So on fair value basis, their revenue would be more like 50 to 60bn. The reason they make 89bn is because they are greedy as hell and they have the right to sell it whatever price they want because ppl buy it for the  brand name. 

So if we consider all that together, it isn‚Äôt really that incredible. What is incredible is that it is actually happening whether I like it or not but if you really apply your logic of fair value, it isn‚Äôt. 

Love their produces when assessed objectively on their merits (except price) but hate the company.

author: @santoshragi
comments:
FYI, Alphabet pays ~$15 billion to Apple for preloading Google search app. All of that ~$15 billion pretty much goes to Apple's bottom line. That payment could stop over time if:
1) new regulations (especially given the shifting sentiment across the world on antitrust regulation) prohibit such preload payments; or 
2) if Alphabet realizes that there is no need for making such a payment as Google search app is likely to be downloaded by the end user.
That's big chunk of cashflow for Apple & they might have to recoup that in other ways. It is for sure a risk to consider.

Hi Sven, I have a question. In your overview now I can see FB Meta 10 % return 205 dollars. In your video in September, there is 413 dollars for 10 % return. Quite a difference, is not it? Does really one miss in quarter earnings have such a huge influence on the overall return, when it is fast growing company with almost no debt? Everybody is so used to that Meta had no or little competition that everybody is very shocked that Meta has to compete with anybody, what a suprise. Is not exactly the stance of value investor to remove the Wall Street noise and know that when a well established company misses one quarter earnings, with 37 % growth of revenue in comparison to 2020, with 36 % growth in EPS in comparison to 2020, there is not a reason to decrease your expected valuation 50 %? At least this is what I learned from your videos and it made me wonder how much is your stance now different from Wall Street analysts and short-term focused investors (speculators). The valuation of 205 dollars price per a common stock for 10 % return seems a rather very very conservative and strange in comparison to 413 dollars published 5 months ago.  
Best regards

author: @Bosshog-WealthHealthBetterment
comments:
Let's be honest, Holmes got a softer sentence because she's female. The sentencing disparity between men and women runs at > 3x the difference between black and white, yet the former is ignored and the latter is held up as a sign of systemic racism. Both the UK and US publish numbers of the subject and see similar ratios. 

In summary, women are seen as being less capable of being devious so when a men is involved they are seen as followers (this was a key argument from Holmes' defence) and they are also more likely to have mitigating circumstances because they look after the elderly and kids at a higher proportion. Not saying either of those reasons are "fair" on women, but we shouldn't ignore what is a clear difference in sentencing purely based on gender. 

Arguably, the most important area of all where equality matters is before the law, and I don't see that at all. Whether you're a Classical Liberal (so right leaning) caring about equality of opportunity, of or a Progressive Liberal (so left leaning) caring about equality of outcome, the whole situation should leave a very poor taste in the mouth. 

Holmes should absolutely have been found similarly guilty. That would be equality worth fighting for.

author: @Allen-L-Canada
comments: Joseph, another insightful show!  I really like the point you make about quantitative and qualitative analysis.  We shouldn't so rigidly focus on the valuation, in some cases such as Buffett's Apple decision, and your CP decision, qualitative aspects such as duration moats will weigh more in decision making.  As Buffett said: it's better to buy a wonderful business at a fair price, than a fair business at a wonderful price.  A practical way to approach this point is this: given two businesses with similar valuations,  we accept a smaller margin of safety (in %) for the business with a more durable moat and vice versa.
